Living in big cities is bad for people's health. To what extent do you agree or disagree

👉 There is a growing concern about the impact of city life on people’s health. While I agree that living in urban areas offers certain health-related benefits, I believe that it also has significant negative effects on individuals’ physical and mental well-being.

👉 On the one hand, living in cities can be beneficial to some extent. Urban residents often have easy access to modern healthcare facilities, including well-equipped hospitals and advanced medical technologies, which enable early diagnosis and effective treatment of diseases such as cancer or diabetes. In addition, cities usually provide a wide range of fitness and recreational centers, allowing people to maintain a healthy lifestyle and relieve stress more easily than those in rural areas.

👉 On the other hand, city life can pose serious health risks. One major issue is noise pollution caused by traffic and construction, which may lead to problems such as sleep disturbances, stress, and even hypertension. Furthermore, air pollution from vehicle emissions and industrial activities is a leading cause of respiratory diseases, heart conditions, and lung cancer. Moreover, heavy traffic congestion and fast-paced lifestyles can increase stress levels, leaving individuals with little time to relax or take care of their well-being.

👉 In conclusion, although living in cities provides better access to healthcare and recreational facilities, I believe that the negative impacts on both physical and mental health are more significant.
